Restore the interrupt flag save/restore, and the OPL2 register writes

Three functions in game2.c bracket a critical section with `pushf` / `disable()`
/ `popf`. Commenting out the assembly leaves the `disable()` with nothing to
undo it: game2.c ends up with three calls to disable() and none to enable().
SetAdLibRegister() is called several hundred times while probing for an AdLib,
so the first one masks interrupts for the rest of the process's life, the timer
interrupt never lands, and every WaitHard() spins forever.

`pushf`/`popf` are replaced by explicit save and restore of the interrupt flag,
which is the only flag the surrounding code cares about.

SetAdLibRegister() also loses its actual work when the assembly goes: the OUTs
to the OPL2 address and data ports were in there. Those come back as ordinary
outportb() calls. The long runs of `in` instructions are not restored -- they
existed purely to burn the microseconds the physical chip needed between
diff --git a/game2.c b/game2.c
index c998238..6244894 100644
--- a/game2.c
+++ b/game2.c
@@ -271,24 +271,14 @@ hardware to process the write and become ready for another (potential) write.
 */
